class Solution {
public:
    string removeOccurrences(string s, string part) {
        while (s.find(part) != string::npos) {
            s.erase(s.find(part), part.length());
        }
        return s;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n*m)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a while loop to continuously find and remove the substring 'part' from string 's' until it's no longer found. The erase function is used to remove the found substring. The time complexity is O(n*m) because in the worst case, we might have to traverse the entire string 's' for each character in 'part'. The space complexity is O(1) because we're not using any additional space that scales with input size.

